<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-028-242 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 465 747</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Oct 28 1991 v13 n43 p55(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>XBase after Ashton-Tate: after the fall, developers confront afractured database standard, OOP, and client/server computing.andO;(XBase is dBase language compatibility, object-orientedprogramming)(Perspectives)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mace, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The future of dBase as the language standard for data basemanagement system (DBMS) software is uncertain in the wake of alawsuit between developer Ashton-Tate Corp and Fox Software Incand because of dBase IV's failure to provide transparent access todatabases.andP;  Filling the void are XBase products, such as FoxPro2.0 DBMS, which are compatible with the dBase language.andP;  Theproblem is that versions of XBase products are not portable, andwithout standards, development and training costs rise.andP;  Theincreased popularity of object-oriented programming (OOP) makesthe lack of standards less detrimental, but it will not draw usersto XBase; XBase must become more user-friendly.andP;  Two otherquestions facing developers are whether XBase is an acceptablebridge to server data and whether it can be used for downsizing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ashton-Tate (Products)Fox Software Inc. (Products).andO;Ticker:    TATE.andO;Product:   dBASE (Data base management system) (Usage)FoxPro 2.0 (Data base management system) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Compatible SoftwareStandardizationFuture of ComputingData base management systemsSoftware DesignProgramming LanguagesObject-Oriented Programming.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Top 10 reasons XBase will remain a standard in the 1990s. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>